slidetranscripts.Text: So, you are thinking about becoming a Step UP coach, and you are wondering whether coaching is for you. Perhaps you are not even clear about exactly what Step UP is and what your responsibilities would be if you decide to become a coach. This short introduction may help answer your questions and provide a quick overview of Step UP.

So, you are thinking about becoming a Step UP coach, and you are wondering whether coaching is for you. Perhaps you are not even clear about exactly what Step UP is and what your responsibilities would be if you decide to become a coach. This short introduction may help answer your questions and provide a quick overview of Step UP.

¡Step UP is a program that pairs a student with a faculty, administrator or staff coach

¡They meet once a week for about an hour; there is no agenda.

¡The student leads the conversation and is free to talk about anything.

¡The coach is there to support and encourage the student.

üThe program is entirely volunteer. All of the coaches and all of the students volunteer.

üYou have what it takes to be a step up coach. Just participating in this brief module shows you have interest in supporting our students.

üIt is the relationship between the coach and student that makes a successful coaching experience.

üLikely you already possess 99% of what you need to be a good coach by simply caring and listening.

ü You can learn the other 1% in these modules and in other Step Up Training.

The Step UP program is voluntary. Both coaches and students are volunteering to participate in the program. Without coaches the program simply would not exist. That is why your participation is so important.

Click on each step to see the Impact of Step UP at HCC!

·Step UP is far-reaching; coaches represent all areas of the College. It is truly a cross-constituency program.

·Over 1200 Students have participated in Step UP. More than 300 administrators, staff and faculty, full-time and part-time, have become Step UP coaches.

·Step UP serves a wide range of students, full-time and part-time from a variety of disciplines.

·Step UP students are more likely to re-enroll in classes at HCC than students who are not in the program.

·The results of Step UP have been impressive. Data shows that on average, Step UP students have a higher GPA than students who do not participate in the program.

You may be wondering exactly what is meant by coaching. Perhaps it is easier to clarify by describing what coaching is not.

·Coaching is not counseling. A coach is not there to "fix" a broken student. Though you may hear about personal problems, the role of the coach is to support and, if appropriate, encourage the student to get professional help from the Counseling Center.

 

·Coaching is not advising. You do not need to know college requirements nor what courses your student should take next semester. Though students may want to discuss goals and classes, the role of the coach is to support and then encourage them to see an advisor to plan their academic future.

 

·Coaching is not teaching. You do not need to be a content expert in order to coach. Your students may come to you with academic questions, but your role is to support them and encourage them to speak with their teachers about academic concerns or perhaps encourage them to sign up for tutoring.

·What then is coaching?

·The heart of Step UP is the coach/student relationship. Coaches and students forge close, trusting bonds.

·The job of the coach is to listen closely without judging. Think of yourself as a cheerleader, someone who is there to celebrate successes and help the students through difficult times.

·A good coach listens more than talks and asks powerful questions. Questions that help students think more deeply about themselves.

·Coaches may refer students to resources that address student concerns or questions.

·Click next to see the video on the impact a Step UP coach has on a student.
Now that weve shared a little about coaching, what do you think you need to be a coach? Select all that apply.

Step UP and coaching are likely new to you, and we want you to be comfortable. Here you will find the steps you need to take to begin coaching.

Step 1: You will need to attend one training session before you begin coaching. Monthly meetings are held to further your coach training, share experiences, and meet other colleagues who are also coaching. Though the meetings are not required, they are always helpful, and you are encouraged to attend when time permits. Professional development credit is provided for training sessions.

Step 2: You are asked to set aside one hour per week to meet with your student in a place free of distractions. Face-to-face meetings are the norm, but occasionally you may want to check in via a phone call or chat. :Careful data is kept so that we can clearly show the impact of Step UP. To facilitate accurate data collection, coaches are asked to keep track of student attendance and to let the Director of Step UP know if the student never attends or stops attending meetings

Step 3: Accurate record keeping is essential for program success measurements. You will need to complete and turn in your coaching log at the end of the semester.

·The Step UP leadership team coordinates the program. They have been working together for a long time, and they know the program inside out. If you have any concerns at all about your student, your role, or the program itself, contact a member of the leadership team.

·Monthly Step UP meetings provide a forum for asking questions and enhancing your coaching skills. A different topic each month is chosen to address coaching issues.

·Step UP has a robust Canvas site. Electronic copies of Step UP forms are placed there as well as copies of workshop presentations from years ago through current sessions. Step UP training modules are also housed on the Canvas site. Directions for using Canvas are in the Step UP manual.

 

 The Step UP manual is a great reference tool. There you will find hard copies of Step UP forms, important dates and times for the semester, coaching tips, and an extensive list of student resources available at HCC.

·As a Step UP coach, you will be joining colleagues from all areas of the college. It's a great opportunity to meet peers you wouldn't ordinarily interact with. They are there to help you if you have questions, if you just want to chat or share experiences or brainstorm for new coaching strategies
Now that you have a better understanding on what coaching is, what do you think an HCC student can expect from the Step UP program?

You already have what it takes to be a good coach if you

·care about students

·can listen without judging

·can ask questions that help students think about their lives, goals, and concerns

·want to make a difference in one student's life

·can spare one hour a week to meet with a student

·Click next to get a taste of coaching. You will see how a coach initiates a session, listens without judgement and asks powerful questions.

Theres so much we want to share with you about the impact that Step Up can make on the student experience at HCC.

Hopefully, this introduction has been informative, and you will want to join your colleagues by becoming a Step UP coach.

Are you ready to show students they matter?

If so, please contact the Director of Step UP to sign up at stepup@howardcc.edu or call 443-518-4465.
